{"info": {"author": "Matthew Spellings", "author_email": "mspells@umich.edu", "bugtrack_url": null, "classifiers": ["Development Status :: 3 - Alpha", "License :: OSI Approved :: BSD License", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Topic :: Multimedia :: Graphics", "Topic :: Scientific/Engineering :: Visualization"], "description": "=================================\nWelcome to plato's documentation!\n=================================\n\nPlato is designed for efficient visualization of particle data. Think\nof it sort of like matplotlib, but being less focused on 2D plotting.\n\nInstallation\n============\n\nPlato is available on PyPI for installation via pip::\n\n  $ pip install plato-draw\n\nYou can also install plato from source, like this::\n\n   $ git clone https://github.com/glotzerlab/plato.git\n   $ # now install\n   $ cd plato && python setup.py install\n\n.. note::\n\n   Depending on which backends you want to use, there may be\n   additional steps required; see the section on interactive backends\n   below.\n\nUsing Interactive Backends\n--------------------------\n\nPlato contains a number of backends, each with its own set of\ndependencies. Getting the vispy backend working for both the desktop\nand jupyter notebook can be tricky. Make sure to check the official\n`vispy documentation <http://vispy.org/installation.html>`_. We also\nkeep some advice `here\n<https://bitbucket.org/snippets/glotzer/nMg8Gr/plato-dependency-installation-tips>`_\nregarding particular known-good versions of dependencies for pip and\nconda.\n\nDocumentation\n=============\n\nThe documentation is available as standard sphinx documentation::\n\n  $ cd doc\n  $ make html\n\nAutomatically-built documentation is available at\nhttps://plato-draw.readthedocs.io .\n\nExamples\n========\n\nSeveral usage examples are available. Many simple, but less\ninteresting, scenes can be found in `the test demo scene script\n<https://github.com/glotzerlab/plato/blob/master/test/test_scenes.py>`_,\navailable as `live examples on mybinder.org\n<https://mybinder.org/v2/gh/glotzerlab/plato/master?filepath=examples>`_. Somewhat\nless transparent examples can be found in `the plato-gallery\nrepository <https://github.com/glotzerlab/plato-gallery>`_.\n\n\n\n", "description_content_type": "", "docs_url": null, "download_url": "", "downloads": {"last_day": -1, "last_month": -1, "last_week": -1}, "home_page": "", "keywords": "", "license": "BSD-3-Clause", "maintainer": "", "maintainer_email": "", "name": "plato-draw", "package_url": "https://pypi.org/project/plato-draw/", "platform": "", "project_url": "https://pypi.org/project/plato-draw/", "project_urls": {"Documentation": "http://plato-draw.readthedocs.io/", "Source": "https://github.com/glotzerlab/plato"}, "release_url": "https://pypi.org/project/plato-draw/1.10.0/", "requires_dist": ["numpy", "scipy", "rowan", "pyside ; extra == 'pyside'", "vispy (>=0.5.3) ; extra == 'pyside'", "pyside2 ; extra == 'pyside2'", "vispy (>=0.6) ; extra == 'pyside2'", "pythreejs ; extra == 'pythreejs'"], "requires_python": ">=3", "summary": "Geometry and visualization tools for collections of particles", "version": "1.10.0", "yanked": false, "html_description": "<div class=\"project-description\">\n            <p>Plato is designed for efficient visualization of particle data. Think\nof it sort of like matplotlib, but being less focused on 2D plotting.</p>\n<div id=\"installation\">\n<h2>Installation</h2>\n<p>Plato is available on PyPI for installation via pip:</p>\n<pre>$ pip install plato-draw\n</pre>\n<p>You can also install plato from source, like this:</p>\n<pre>$ git clone https://github.com/glotzerlab/plato.git\n$ # now install\n$ cd plato &amp;&amp; python setup.py install\n</pre>\n<div>\n<p>Note</p>\n<p>Depending on which backends you want to use, there may be\nadditional steps required; see the section on interactive backends\nbelow.</p>\n</div>\n<div id=\"using-interactive-backends\">\n<h3>Using Interactive Backends</h3>\n<p>Plato contains a number of backends, each with its own set of\ndependencies. Getting the vispy backend working for both the desktop\nand jupyter notebook can be tricky. Make sure to check the official\n<a href=\"http://vispy.org/installation.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">vispy documentation</a>. We also\nkeep some advice <a href=\"https://bitbucket.org/snippets/glotzer/nMg8Gr/plato-dependency-installation-tips\" rel=\"nofollow\">here</a>\nregarding particular known-good versions of dependencies for pip and\nconda.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div id=\"documentation\">\n<h2>Documentation</h2>\n<p>The documentation is available as standard sphinx documentation:</p>\n<pre>$ cd doc\n$ make html\n</pre>\n<p>Automatically-built documentation is available at\n<a href=\"https://plato-draw.readthedocs.io\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://plato-draw.readthedocs.io</a> .</p>\n</div>\n<div id=\"examples\">\n<h2>Examples</h2>\n<p>Several usage examples are available. Many simple, but less\ninteresting, scenes can be found in <a href=\"https://github.com/glotzerlab/plato/blob/master/test/test_scenes.py\" rel=\"nofollow\">the test demo scene script</a>,\navailable as <a href=\"https://mybinder.org/v2/gh/glotzerlab/plato/master?filepath=examples\" rel=\"nofollow\">live examples on mybinder.org</a>. Somewhat\nless transparent examples can be found in <a href=\"https://github.com/glotzerlab/plato-gallery\" rel=\"nofollow\">the plato-gallery\nrepository</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n          </div>"}, "last_serial": 6896149, "releases": {"1.0.0": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "5e9becd41a0e239d032974a272a956d6", "sha256": "2682d011d3230ee7c8b9b67826974bd97198f1e74b37fe74d7d857353e433d57"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "plato_draw-1.0.0-py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "5e9becd41a0e239d032974a272a956d6", "packagetype": "bdist_wheel", "python_version": "py3", "requires_python": ">=3", "size": 79127, "upload_time": "2018-04-16T18:09:04", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2018-04-16T18:09:04.365552